{% set board = cropsThatLoseMarginWhenPlantedLate %}
{% set top = board.top %}

<section class="card leaderboardHero">
  <p class="eyebrow">Crop timing comparison</p>
  <h1>Crops That Lose the Most Margin When Planted Late</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Some crops forgive a late start. Others quickly lose the heat margin they need before fall frost.
    A two-week delay does not hurt every crop equally. This comparison shows which crops lose the most heat and maturity margin when planting slips later than planned.
  </p>

  <div class="leaderboardStatGrid" aria-label="Ranking summary">
    {% if top %}
      <div class="leaderboardStat">
        <span class="statLabel">Highest pressure crop</span>
        <strong>{{ top.cropName }}</strong>
        <span>{{ top.score }}/100 · {{ top.label }}</span>
      </div>
    {% endif %}

    <div class="leaderboardStat">
      <span class="statLabel">Crops compared</span>
      <strong>{{ board.entries.length }}</strong>
      <span>Crops with two-week delay data</span>
    </div>

    <div class="leaderboardStat">
      <span class="statLabel">Best used for</span>
      <strong>Late starts</strong>
      <span>Prioritizing crops when spring timing slips</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The ranking</h2>
  <p>
    Crops rank higher when they lose more heat margin after a two-week planting delay, especially when that delay pushes more locations
    into negative maturity margin. The score is designed for practical late-season decisions: which crops should be protected, transplanted,
    started first, switched to faster varieties, or dropped when the planting window gets tight.
  </p>

  <div class="tableWrap leaderboardTableWrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Rank</th>
          <th>Crop</th>
          <th>Pressure score</th>
          <th>Two-week margin loss</th>
          <th>Avg. late margin</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {% for row in board.entries %}
          <tr>
            <td><strong>#{{ row.rank }}</strong></td>
            <td><strong>{{ row.cropName }}</strong><br><span class="small muted">{{ row.publishedLocations }} modeled locations</span></td>
            <td><strong>{{ row.score }}/100</strong></td>
            <td>{{ row.averageTwoWeekMarginLoss }} GDD</td>
            <td>{{ row.averageTwoWeekLateMargin }} GDD</td>
          </tr>
        {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to read this ranking</h2>
  <p>
    This page is not only measuring how many growing degree days disappear from the calendar. It also looks at what that loss does to the crop’s remaining margin.
    A crop with a high late-planting pressure score is one where a two-week delay can quickly turn a comfortable season into a tight one.
  </p>
  <p>
    The <strong>two-week margin loss</strong> column shows the average amount of heat margin removed by a two-week delay. The <strong>average late margin</strong> column shows
    how much cushion remains after that delay. A crop can be risky even when the margin loss looks similar to another crop, because the important question is whether enough
    heat is still left to mature before frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Visual chart</h2>
  <p>
    For a more visual version of this ranking, see the <a href="/data/late-planting-penalty-chart/">Late Planting Penalty Chart</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card leaderboardCallout">
  <h2>What this ranking means</h2>
  <p>
    A high score does not mean the crop is impossible. It means late planting is more expensive: the crop loses more of its available heat window,
    and the difference between “probably fine” and “too tight” can shrink quickly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Late planting is usually most punishing when a crop has a long maturity window, a high heat requirement, slow establishment, or very little remaining cushion after the normal planting date.
    In short-season gardens, those problems can compound. A small delay in spring can become a much larger risk at harvest because cool late-summer weather adds heat more slowly than warm early-summer weather.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What to do when timing is tight</h2>
  <p>
    If a crop ranks high on this list, treat timing as part of the crop plan. That can mean using healthy transplants, choosing faster-maturing varieties,
    planting into the warmest available microclimate, adding temporary protection, or switching to a crop with more timing flexibility.
  </p>
  <p>
    For a location-specific answer, use the <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">GDD planner</a> or compare the crop against
    <a href="/data/crop-heat-requirements/">Crop Heat Requirements</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Crop-specific late planting guides</h2>
  <p>
    This ranking shows which crops lose the most margin after a two-week delay. If you are deciding whether a specific crop is still worth planting,
    use the crop guides below.
  </p>
